<bill id="DLM1630000" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2010" bill.no="302" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2008">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Māori Affairs Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM2831860" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="302" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2008">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Māori Affairs Committee has examined the Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Bill, and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Bill would give effect to a Deed of Settlement signed by the Crown and Waikato-Tainui on 22 August 2008. We received submissions on the bill, but deferred hearing evidence on it after the Minister for Treaty of Waitangi Negotiations wrote to us expressing concern about the workability and efficiency of the co-management framework set out in the bill. The Minister established an independent review panel to review and report on the Waikato River co-management arrangements. Following the report, the Crown and Waikato River iwi undertook negotiations leading to a revised Deed of Settlement being signed on 17 December 2009. We have now been asked to consider the bill, taking account of these amendments.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We invited certain groups to make submissions on the proposed amendments to the bill. Our commentary covers the major amendments we recommend to reflect the co-management arrangements agreed under the revised Deed of Settlement. We also comment on the main issues that arose in our consideration of the second phase of public consultation. We do not comment on the minor and technical amendments required as a consequence of the major amendments to the bill.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Focus of recommended amendments</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The revised Deed of Settlement would streamline the co-governance and co-management arrangements, and retain the clean-up fund. It would establish a single co-governance entity, the Waikato River Authority. The previous Deed of Settlement would have led to the establishment of five statutory boards. The Authority would be made up of equal numbers of Crown- and iwi-appointed members, including representatives of other iwi with interests along the river. It would be responsible for monitoring the implementation of a direction-setting document, the <emphasis style="italic">Vision and Strategy, Te Ture Whaimana</emphasis>.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend significant amendments to the bill to reflect the revised governance and co-management arrangements arising from the new Deed of Settlement. In summary, these changes affect seven key provisions of the bill as introduced.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Governance functions relating to the Waikato River would be consolidated in a single co-governance entity to be known as the Waikato River Authority.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The direction-setting document to be administered by the Waikato River Authority, the Vision and Strategy, would no longer have the status of a national policy statement; instead, it would be designated <quote.in quote="1">Te Ture Whaimana</quote.in> and become the primary direction-setting document for the Waikato River, taking precedence over national policy statements and other planning documents under the Resource Management Act 1991.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Waikato River Clean-up Trust would then be established in legislation and the Trust’s contestable fund would be administered by the Waikato River Authority rather than by separate trustees.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Iwi-appointed commissioners would participate in hearing committees and boards of inquiry in respect of applications for resource consents to take, use, dam, or divert water in the Waikato River; for point-source discharge to the Waikato River; and for certain activities in relation to the Waikato River, which are listed in section 13 of the Resource Management Act 1991.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Joint management agreements would be required between Waikato-Tainui and the Waikato Regional Council and between Waikato-Tainui and relevant territorial authorities for specified functions under the Resource Management Act 1991 insofar as those functions related to the Waikato River and activities within its catchment affecting the Waikato River.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Certain specified customary activities of Waikato-Tainui in relation to the Waikato River would be recognised.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Provision would be made to vest certain river-related sites of significance in Waikato-Tainui; to vest certain Crown-owned lands administered for flood protection purposes in Waikato-Tainui, who would gift those lands to the Waikato Regional Council; and for Waikato-Tainui to participate in the co-management of Crown-owned river-related lands.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We have structured our commentary under thematic headings covering the principal changes proposed to the bill so as to reflect the provisions of the revised Deed of Settlement. This means that changes to particular clauses are not discussed in strictly numerical order.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Single co-governance entity</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the establishment of a new entity,<emphasis style="bold"> </emphasis>the Waikato River Authority, to be the co-governance entity for the Waikato River and to replace the Guardians of the Waikato River and the Waikato River Statutory Board proposed under the 2008 Deed of Settlement with Waikato-Tainui. The Waikato River Authority would also replace other statutory entities proposed in negotiations with other Waikato River and Waipā River iwi.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Consolidating the co-governance arrangements into a single entity was negotiated by the Crown and agreed by Waikato-Tainui to remove the risk of ambiguity as to roles under the previous model which comprised multiple structures and entities. The new arrangements are designed to promote focused governance, good process, and effective outcomes.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Waikato River Authority would be established through the settlement legislation on the following basis:</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>50:50 Crown-Māori membership, with one Crown member nominated by Environment Waikato and one nominated by relevant territorial authorities.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>Membership of ten including one Crown-appointed co-chair and one iwi-appointed co-chair.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>Iwi members to be appointed by Waikato-Tainui, Raukawa, Ngāti Tūwharetoa, Maniapoto, and Te Arawa River iwi.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>Crown members to be appointed by the Minister for the Environment in consultation with other Ministers.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The purpose of the Waikato River Authority would be to</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>provide direction through the Vision and Strategy to achieve the restoration and protection of the health and well-being of the Waikato River for future generations</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>promote an integrated, holistic, and co-ordinated approach to the implementation of the Vision and Strategy and the management of the Waikato River</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>fund rehabilitation initiatives for the Waikato River, in its role as trustee for the Waikato River Clean-up Trust.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The functions of the Waikato River Authority would include</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>advising on giving effect to the Vision and Strategy</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>acting as trustee of the Waikato River Clean-up Trust</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>carrying out effectiveness monitoring and reporting</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>periodically reviewing the Vision and Strategy</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>requesting call-ins under the Resource Management Act 1991</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>appointing iwi commissioners to river-related resource consent hearings (detailed below).</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Waikato River Authority would be supported by a secretariat dedicated to the Authority and funded by the Crown for reasonable operational costs.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We note the submission from Watercare Services that at least one member of the Waikato River Authority should be appointed to represent Auckland’s water supply needs. While we support this suggestion, we are aware that any change to the membership would require agreement between the Crown and Waikato-Tainui and an amendment to the revised Deed of Settlement. We therefore suggest that the Minister consider nominating one of the five Crown nominees to the Authority from Watercare Services.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also considered but did not support a request from Ngāti Koroki Kahukura Trust to amend the membership provisions proposed for the Waikato River Authority to include one member appointed on their recommendation. We consider that the size of the proposed Waikato River Authority needs to remain at a maximum of 10 members to be workable.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We are mindful, however, that the Authority would replace previous entities that did include a right of membership for the iwi and that their mana should be respected. We have been assured that other avenues are being investigated to ensure that the iwi’s interests are protected and that their voice is heard in respect of their Tupuna Awa.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Vision and Strategy for the Waikato River</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that<emphasis style="bold"> </emphasis>the Vision and Strategy no longer have the status of a national policy statement, but become the primary direction-setting document for the Waikato River, and be called <quote.in quote="1">Te Ture Whaimana</quote.in>.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Crown and Waikato-Tainui have agreed to new provisions to ensure that the Vision and Strategy sets clear direction for those with statutory and management responsibilities for the Waikato River and to provide certainty about its status under legislation pertaining to the Waikato River.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The key elements of the new framework are as follows:</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>The Vision and Strategy would be incorporated directly into the Waikato regional policy statement.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>The Vision and Strategy would be reviewed by the Waikato River Authority to add targets and methods, giving it more specificity and better alignment with the objectives set out in the Deed of Settlement.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>No other part of the Waikato regional policy statement relating to the Waikato River could be inconsistent with the Vision and Strategy.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>The Vision and Strategy would be given effect under the Resource Management Act 1991 through the regional and district plans.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>The Vision and Strategy would be given the status of a statement of general policy under conservation legislation.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>The Vision and Strategy would be given <quote.in quote="1">have particular regard to</quote.in> status under 20 Acts listed in the bill (clause 11).</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>The Vision and Strategy would prevail over any inconsistent provision in a national policy statement or a New Zealand coastal policy statement that related to the Waikato River.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>Rules in regional and district plans giving effect to the Vision and Strategy would prevail if they were more stringent than national environmental standards, water conservation orders, or bylaws.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>Under the Energy Efficiency and Conservation Act 2000, Land Transport Management Act 2003, and Foreshore and Seabed Act 2004 the Vision and Strategy would be treated on the same basis as if it were a national policy statement.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>New clause 9B(1) would provide for the inclusion of the Vision and Strategy in the Waikato regional policy statement without using the Resource Management Act’s schedule 1 process. Some submitters suggested that a board of inquiry should first be appointed to determine how the Vision and Strategy would be incorporated into the regional policy statement and consequential changes to regional and district plans.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Incorporation of the Vision and Strategy directly into the regional policy statement is a key element of the settlement with Waikato-Tainui. In new clause 13A we propose that within three months of the settlement date the Waikato River Authority be required to review the Vision and Strategy by a process akin to a board of inquiry; and new clause 9D would require the regional council and local authorities to update their planning documents to conform with the reviewed Vision and Strategy. These processes would be subject to public consultation.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We consider that the only real difference between the proposed amendments to the bill and the submitter’s proposal is that, under the bill, the Vision and Strategy would become part of the regional policy statement immediately (that is, before it was reviewed) whereas the submitter considers the Vision and Strategy should not become part of the regional policy statement until it has been reviewed. We note that this process was agreed upon through lengthy consultation and that councils did not raise this as an issue with us. Accordingly we do not support delaying the incorporation of the Vision and Strategy into the regional policy statement.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We were also asked to consider amending clause 9 of the bill as introduced so that reviews of regional and district plans would be required after the review of the regional policy statement that will occur once it incorporates the Vision and Strategy.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We were assured that the purpose of the regional policy statement review would be to ensure its consistency with the Vision and Strategy. We recommend amending clause 9D(4) to make it clear that the purpose of reviewing regional and district plans is to ensure they give effect to the regional policy statement and in particular its Vision and Strategy component.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Other submitters were concerned about the alignment of the review process for the Vision and Strategy with the review of other planning documents. In particular, it was suggested that the proposed cycle for subsequent reviews of the Vision and Strategy would result in 5-yearly reviews, whereas other planning documents are reviewed on a 10-yearly cycle.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>New clause 13B proposes a requirement for subsequent reviews <quote.in quote="1">no earlier than 5 years and no later than 10 years after the previous review</quote.in>. The starting date of any review would in any case be linked to the initial review of the Vision and Strategy and thus would not align with the review cycle of planning documents under the Resource Management Act 1991. We consider that the Waikato River Authority should have the flexibility of a 5-to-10-year window for undertaking reviews rather than an arbitrary requirement to review once every 10 years, and do not recommend further changes.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Waikato River Clean-up Trust</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending the bill to provide for the establishment of the Waikato River Clean-up Trust and to set out the terms of Trust.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Waikato River Authority would be the trustee of the Waikato River Clean-up Trust. The object of the Trust is the restoration and protection of the health and well-being of the Waikato River for future generations.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Trust fund would be available on a contestable basis for use in projects proposed by any organisation or members of the community to achieve the object of the Trust.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The Crown would contribute $210 million over 30 years for the purposes of the Waikato River Clean-up Trust.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Iwi participation in resource consent decision-making concerning the Waikato River</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amendments to the provisions in the bill as introduced for iwi participation in resource consent decision-making as it affects the Waikato River. The Waikato River Authority would maintain a list of accredited commissioners appointed by Waikato-Tainui, Raukawa, Ngāti Tūwharetoa, Maniapoto, and Te Arawa River iwi. The Waikato River Authority would appoint commissioners from the list to Waikato Regional Council hearing committees (for notified applications) and boards of inquiry (in the event of a call-in) in respect of the following kinds of resource consent applications:</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>applications to take, use, dam, or divert water from or in the Waikato River</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>applications to make point-source discharges to the Waikato River</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>applications to carry out certain activities in relation to the Waikato River, as listed in section 13 of the Resource Management Act 1991.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>In the case of a regional council hearing committee, the committee would comprise accredited commissioners appointed by the council, an equal number of accredited iwi commissioners appointed by the Waikato River Authority, and an independent chair.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>In the case of a board of inquiry on a call-in, the committee would comprise members appointed by the Minister for the Environment, an equal number of accredited iwi commissioners appointed by the Waikato River Authority, and a chair who would be a current, former, or retired Environment Judge or a retired High Court Judge as required by the Resource Management Act 1991.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Some submitters expressed concern about the technical competence of members of hearing committees, in view of the complexity of tools and instruments under the Resource Management Act 1991. We consider the proposed amendments (new clauses 18C and 18D) are appropriate and have no concern that the Minister and the iwi, when recommending a person for appointment, would not ensure that members have the skills, knowledge, and experience to participate effectively.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Joint management agreements</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending the provisions in the bill concerning joint management agreements. The Waikato Regional Council and territorial authorities whose boundaries fall within, or partly within, the lower Waikato River catchment (from Karapiro to the mouth of the river) would be required to establish joint management agreements with Waikato-Tainui. This would not include the Auckland Council.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending the bill to define the scope of matters to be covered by joint management agreements to include matters that relate to the Waikato River and any activities in its catchment that affect the Waikato River. As amended the bill would specify four categories of matters under the Resource Management Act 1991 that must be included in the joint management agreements:</text>
          <list>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>reviews of the Waikato regional policy statement, to ensure consistency with the Vision and Strategy, and reviews of regional and district plans to give effect to the Vision and Strategy</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>setting monitoring priorities, reviewing results, and identifying responses</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>the processing stages (as distinct from decision-making, which is dealt with above) for resource consent applications to the Waikato Regional Council to undertake any activities affecting the Waikato River (as set out in new clause 29G)</text>
              </para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
              <para>
                <text>the processing stages (as distinct from decision-making) for resource consent applications to territorial authorities for the use of or activities on the surface of the water in the Waikato River.</text>
              </para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend making it clear that the statutory basis of joint management agreements would be provided through the settlement legislation, when it was enacted. Once established, any such agreement could not be terminated, and could be suspended only by agreement of the parties. All members of hearing committees would have to be accredited under a programme approved and notified under section 39A of the Resource Management Act 1991 (new clauses 18 and 18C).</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recognition of customary activities</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending the bill by inserting new Schedule 2A to reflect the provisions of the revised Deed of Settlement, and make it clear that the bill would recognise and provide for the exercise of customary activities by members of Waikato-Tainui.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Specified customary activities (with associated temporary structures) could be carried out on the Waikato River (including lakes in the catchment) by members of Waikato-Tainui without the need for resource consents or other permits and, subject to sufficient advance notice, would have priority in the event of a competing activity in the same area.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>New clause 30 would provide for a statutory acknowledgement of the importance of the specified customary activities to Waikato-Tainui and their relationship with the Waikato River as a matter to be recognised and provided for under the Resource Management Act 1991.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The joint management agreement between Waikato-Tainui and the Waikato Regional Council would provide for matters relevant to carrying out customary activities, such as consideration of appropriate rules in the Waikato regional plan.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Existing Waikato-Tainui whitebait stands and eel weirs would be allowed to remain without need for resource consents.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>With the approval of the Waikato Raupatu River Trust, members of Waikato-Tainui would be able to carry out on the Waikato River tribally significant tangihanga (funeral ceremonies) or hari tūpāpaku (transportation of human remains) without the need for resource consents or other permits. Future statutory authorisations granted by a local authority in respect of the use of the Waikato River would be deemed to include a condition giving precedence to approved tangihanga and hari tūpāpaku.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Members of Waikato-Tainui carrying out customary activities would have to comply with statutory health and safety requirements; and the Minister for the Environment and the Waikato Raupatu River Trust could intervene if an authorised customary activity were causing, or likely to cause, a significant adverse effect on the environment.</text>
        </para>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Cultural harvest</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amending the cultural harvest provisions in the bill as introduced. New clause 30F would allow Waikato-Tainui to authorise iwi members to harvest flora material for cultural purposes in accordance with a flora cultural harvest plan to be agreed with the Director-General of Conservation. The regulation-making power under the bill would extend to cultural use of wildlife materials and marine mammal materials.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Crown-owned river-related lands and sites of significance to Waikato-Tainui</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amendments to the co-management provisions in the bill for specific Crown-owned river-related lands. As amended the bill would then require co-management arrangements to be entered into with Waikato-Tainui in respect of any Crown-owned river-related lands listed in the revised Deed of Settlement.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Approximately 133 parcels of land held by the Ministry for the Environment and administered by the Waikato Regional Council for soil conservation and river control purposes would be vested in Waikato-Tainui. Nine of these parcels are sites of significance to Waikato-Tainui but would remain subject to continued management by the Waikato Regional Council (under a co-management arrangement with Waikato-Tainui) for soil conservation and river control purposes.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Waikato-Tainui would gift the remaining parcels to the Waikato Regional Council for soil conservation and river control purposes. Waikato-Tainui would have an ongoing role in the co-management of these parcels. If in future these parcels were no longer required for soil conservation and river control purposes the Waikato Regional Council would be required to return them to Waikato-Tainui, subject to first clearing any statutory requirements under the Public Works Act 1981 (such as any requirement for another public work, or offer back to original owner).</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Fifteen other parcels of land with cultural significance for Waikato-Tainui would be vested in Waikato-Tainui, who could elect to have them held in the name of Pōtatau Te Wherowhero or the Waikato Raupatu River Trust.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>These fifteen parcels are currently administered by the Department of Conservation (12) and Land Information New Zealand (3, including the bed of Lake Waikare). The terms of the gifting require the protection of conservation values, public access, and any pre-existing third-party interests, including those of holders of fishing permits, quota, or catch entitlement. To achieve this, these parcels would be vested as a local-purpose reserve, to be administered by Waikato-Tainui under the Reserves Act 1977.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Ngāti Te Ata o Waiohua</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Ngāti Te Ata o Waiohua and Nganeko Minhinnick told us that they were concerned that the bill, if amended as proposed and passed, would threaten their interests in the Waiuku block (raupatu land) including Maioro, as defined by the Māori Appellate Court and as set out in the revised Deed of Settlement.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We note that, while marginal strips from this block are not listed in the schedule to the bill itself, they are listed in the revised Deed of Settlement. We are anxious that Ngāti Te Ata’s land and interests be protected. We were told that Waikato-Tainui and the Crown are working towards ensuring that these interests are protected. We recommend that Waikato-Tainui, the Crown, and Ngāti Te Ata work together to ensure that Ngāti Te Ata’s interests are protected. On this basis we recommend no further amendments to the bill.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Regulations, bylaws, and accords</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Some submitters were concerned about the effect of the bill on their fishing rights. We do not consider that any fishing rights are threatened by the bill. There is nothing to prevent other river iwi from seeking similar arrangements with respect to waterways in which they have interests. Accords with Waikato-Tainui would not be exclusive, and would not prevent other river iwi from seeking similar instruments in future negotiations with the Crown. Similarly, regulations allowing Waikato-Tainui to manage customary fishing on the Waikato River would relate only to members of Waikato-Tainui and would not prevent other river iwi from seeking similar regulations in future negotiations with the Crown.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Regulations providing for Waikato-Tainui to recommend to the Minister of Fisheries the making of bylaws restricting or prohibiting fishing on the Waikato River are also already possible under the Fisheries Act 1996.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend a minor amendment only to clause 47 to make it clear that the Minister of Fisheries could decline to make a by-law if satisfied that it would have an unduly adverse effect on fishing.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Effect on other Crown-iwi negotiations</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We note the concerns of some submitters about the effect of the proposed co-management arrangements on future negotiations with the Crown. In particular, we note the submissions made by Hauraki Mandated Representatives.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The co-management arrangements with Waikato-Tainui proposed under the amended bill are not exclusive and would not prevent other river iwi from negotiating their own arrangements in the future. Such arrangements could include joint management agreements, iwi environmental management plans, and integrated river management. Similarly, the recognition of customary activities of Waikato-Tainui in relation to the Waikato River would not prevent other river iwi from negotiating similar arrangements, including arrangements affecting any customary activities their members might carry out concerning the Waikato River.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>There were concerns expressed about the effect of the bill on overlapping interests in respect of the Waikato River. While the Waikato River settlement with Waikato-Tainui identifies Crown-owned river-related lands to be co-managed, it does not specify the form these arrangements should take. The specific form of co-management arrangements is subject to the provisions of the Kīngitanga Accord, which specifically require the Crown to assess any overlapping interests and acknowledge that any co-management arrangements may be constrained by overlapping interests.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We similarly considered whether standing order 260 (same bill or amendment not to be proposed in a calendar year) would affect the timing of the introduction of an upper river iwi (Ngāti Tūwharetoa, Raukawa, and Te Arawa River iwi) bill.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We were assured that the deed with each river iwi is independent from the Waikato-Tainui deed. These deeds of settlement have an independent origin. They may have similar provisions, but as each deed and its enacting bill affects a different group of people it would not have the same effect. Hence we are satisfied that the Waikato-Tainui settlement legislation would not impede settlement of the claims of upper river iwi.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix </heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Bill was referred to the Māori Affairs Committee of the 48th Parliament on 23 September 2008. The bill was reinstated in the 49th Parliament on 9 December 2008. The closing date for submissions was 5 February 2009. We made an interim report on the bill, which contained proposals for amendment to the bill arising from the revised Deed of Settlement signed on 17 December 2009. The closing date for further submissions was 19 February 2010.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received and considered 32 submissions from interested groups including iwi organisations, local authorities, and fisheries, farming, and forestry stakeholders on the bill as introduced. We received further comment from 28 submitters on the main changes we outlined in our interim report, and heard from 18 groups and individuals. We received advice from the Office of Treaty Settlements. The Regulations Review Committee reported to us on the powers contained in the provisions as they relate to commencement, regulations, and bylaws, and clauses 2, 14, and 47 of the bill as introduced.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Tau Henare (Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Simon Bridges (from 24 June 2009)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Kelvin Davis</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hone Harawira</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Parekura Horomia</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hekia Parata (until 24 June 2009)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Paul Quinn </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Mita Ririnui</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.appendix>
    </commentary>
